'''''G. I. Joe: A Real American Hero''''' is a 1985 [[action game|action]] [[shoot 'em up]] [[video game]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.gamespot.com/c64/action/gijoe/tech_info.html| publisher = GameSpot| title = G.I. Joe Tech Info| access-date = 2010-02-09}}</ref> It was developed and published by [[Epyx]] for the [[Apple II]] and [[Commodore 64]].<ref name="G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero">{{cite web| url = http://www.mobygames.com/game/gi-joe-a-real-american-hero| publisher = MobyGames| title = G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero| access-date = 2010-02-09}}</ref>

==Gameplay==
At the beginning of the game the player selects a one player or two player game. The objective as one of the members of the G.I. Joe team is to eliminate any threats from [[Cobra Command|Cobra]] and to capture eight Cobra operatives. The game cannot be completed if too many members of either side are placed in jail, other members are released to perpetuate the game.<ref name="allgame">{{cite web| url = http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=31031| title = G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero - Overview| last = House| first = Matthew| publisher = [[Allgame]]| access-date = 2010-01-25| archive-date = 2014-11-15| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20141115155246/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=31031| url-status = dead}}</ref>

Two modes of play are used: overhead [[Vehicular combat game|vehicular combat]] sections, where the player controls a member of the G.I. Joe Special Forces, and one-on-one fights with Cobra operatives. There are different geographical locations, such as woods, desert and arctic tundra.<ref name="G.I. Joe: A Real American Hero"/> 

In the overhead vehicular combat portions of the game, the player selects a vehicle from the ''G.I. Joe'' series, choosing from the [[Dragonfly (G.I. Joe)|Dragonfly]] helicopter, [[Skystriker (G.I. Joe)|Skystriker]] jet, [[MOBAT (G.I. Joe)|M.O.B.A.T.]] tank, or [[V.A.M.P. (G.I. Joe)|V.A.M.P.]] jeep. The player would then play as the vehicles' respecting driver - [[Ace (G.I. Joe)|Ace]], [[Wild Bill (G.I. Joe)|Wild Bill]], [[Steeler (G.I. Joe)|Steeler]], or [[Clutch (G.I. Joe)|Clutch]].<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.1up.com/do/blogEntry?bId=8998991| title = Something Old, Something Blu: G.I. Joe Season 1.1| first = Jeremy| last = Parish| date = 2009-07-21| publisher = 1UP.com| access-date = 2010-02-09| archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20121012091232/http://www.1up.com/do/blogEntry?bId=8998991| archive-date = 2012-10-12| url-status = dead}}</ref>

The one-on-one melee battle portion of the game features twelve available characters from the G.I. Joe team: [[Duke (G.I. Joe)|Duke]], [[Scarlett (G.I. Joe)|Scarlett]], [[Recondo (G.I. Joe)|Recondo]], [[Torpedo (G.I. Joe)|Torpedo]], [[Snake Eyes (G.I. Joe)|Snake Eyes]], [[Roadblock (G.I. Joe)|Roadblock]], [[Spirit (G.I. Joe)|Spirit]], [[Zap (G.I. Joe)|Zap]], [[Gung-Ho (G.I. Joe)|Gung-Ho]], [[Snow Job (G.I. Joe)|Snow Job]], [[Blowtorch (G.I. Joe)|Blowtorch]], and [[Stalker (G.I. Joe)|Stalker]]. The Joes face off against eight Cobras: [[Destro]], the [[Baroness (G.I. Joe)|Baroness]], [[Zartan]] (who takes the form of a Joe character), [[Firefly (G.I. Joe)|Firefly]], [[Cobra Commander]], [[Storm Shadow (G.I. Joe)|Storm Shadow]], [[Major Bludd]], and [[Scrap-Iron]].<ref name="yojoe">{{cite web| url = http://www.yojoe.com/archive/games/joepc.shtml| title = G.I. Joe for Personal Computers| last = Roberts| first = Matt| publisher = YoJoe.com| access-date = 2010-03-20}}</ref> Each playable character has advantages and disadvantages, such as faster-moving characters having less-powerful weapons. There are additional elements in the melee levels that can impede or harm the characters, including various environmental obstacles and non-playable vehicles/automated weapons that shoot at the characters.

==Development==
Epyx was a prime supporter of the Commodore 64 as a gaming platform, with licensed games such as ''G.I. Joe'' as an example.<ref>{{cite web| url = http://www.gamasutra.com/view/feature/1991/a_history_of_gaming_platforms_the_.php?page=5| publisher = Gamasutra| title = A History of Gaming Platforms: The Commodore 64| first1 = Bill| last1 = Loguidice| first2 = Matt| last2 = Barton| date = 2007-10-24| access-date = 2010-02-09}}</ref> The game was designed by Ray Carpenter and Jeff Johannigman, with graphics by Pam Carpenter and music by Bob Vieira.<ref name="GameFAQs">{{cite web| url = http://www.gamefaqs.com/computer/c64/data/571752.html| title = G.I. Joe Release Information for Commodore 64| publisher = GameFAQs| access-date = 2010-02-09}}</ref>

